  "distance": "306.587 km (190.504 miles)",
  "event_preview": "Circuit Zandvoort measures 4.259 km (2.646 mi) and features 14 turns tucked into the dunes of the North Sea coastline in Zandvoort, the Netherlands, 35 kilometres west of Amsterdam. Originally opened in 1948, the circuit hosted the Dutch Grand Prix continuously from 1952 until 1985 before a lengthy absence, returning to the Formula 1 calendar in 2021 on the wave of enthusiasm surrounding Max Verstappen. Two banked corners — the Hugenholtzbocht at Turn 3 and the Arie Luyendijkbocht at Turn 14, both tilted at 18 degrees — are a unique feature not found anywhere else on the calendar, allowing higher cornering speeds and reducing the need to scrub off momentum. With its narrow layout, limited runoff and predominantly flowing character, Zandvoort severely restricts overtaking and places qualifying at the heart of race weekend strategy. The official race lap record stands at 1:11.097, set by Lewis Hamilton for Mercedes during the 2021 Dutch Grand Prix, while the all-time qualifying lap record belongs to Max Verstappen, who clocked a 1:08.885 for Red Bull in Q3 of that same weekend.",
